        <mxCell id="HVv0qu-hVGIwA-nW1s2f-38" value="&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 16px;&quot;&gt;Why&lt;/font&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 14px;&quot;&gt;Handler is an Abstract class and not an interface?&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;0&quot;&gt;In the Chain of Responsibility pattern, we can&amp;nbsp;technically use an interface, but using an &lt;b data-index-in-node=&quot;91&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;0&quot;&gt;abstract class&lt;/b&gt; is the preferred industry standard.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span data-index-in-node=&quot;21&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;b data-index-in-node=&quot;21&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;An abstract class allows you to share common boilerplate code, whereas an interface forces every single handler to duplicate that code.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;b data-index-in-node=&quot;21&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;1.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;span data-index-in-node=&quot;21&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;Centralized Chain Management (Boilerplate Reduction)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;&lt;span data-index-in-node=&quot;21&quot; data-path-to-node=&quot;1&quot;&gt;2.&amp;nbsp;Standardizing the Pass-Through Behavior using a&lt;b&gt; Template Method&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;" style="shape=callout;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;perimeter=calloutPerimeter;" vertex="1" parent="1">
          <mxGeometry x="470" y="-180" width="370" height="260" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
